history: speaker1: Hello, I just finished my daily run outside.
speaker2: Cool, do you compete running or just stay fit.
speaker1: Just do it exercise and leisure! What do you do?
speaker2: I play video games, mostly with friends.
speaker1: Cool, I have never played video games but I would to try.
speaker2: League of legends is my favorite and alistar is my favorite champion.
speaker1: I have heard of league of legends my friends play that.
speaker2: Last month I bought a new gaming laptop which is really cool.
speaker1: Wow, I don't enjoy computer games that much. I like to be outside.
speaker2: I understand, do you do exercise other than running.
speaker1: I like to swim too, I also enjoy walking my dog..
speaker2: Swimming is good for you too.
speaker1: How has the new gaming laptop been working for you when you play League of Legends?
speaker2: It's been great. Works really well, great visuals. I know you're not a gamer, but I'd highly recommend the brand if you were ever in the market for a computer.
speaker1: You are right, but all my friends like to play! I just got through with my first marathon. It was a real challenge.
speaker2: Oh gosh I can only imagine! How did you feel at the end of it?
speaker1: I was drained and dehydrated. I always run at a faster pace when I'm in a crowd of people and it really got to me.
speaker2: I have to admit, I've never been much of a runner unless I'm being chased, lol! I do enjoy swimming, though.
speaker1: That's another one of favorite activities. I'm a better runner than a swimmer however.
speaker2: Swimming feels so good on my knees. They get so sore. Have you ever tried getting your dog to swim with you?
speaker1: Yes! I go some in the lake and my dog loves it. I guess it is true. Dogs are man's best friend.
speaker2: Haha, my poor dog is so ridiculous. She's terrified of a bath, but she loves to jump into a muddy lake.
speaker1: I need to take a run or swim tomorrow before I get too lazy!!!
speaker2: Now that it's getting warmer swimming will feel really good.
speaker1: My dog and I are checking out a new lake this weekend. Hopefully it isn't too muddy.
speaker2: Sound fantastic, what kind of dog do you have?
speaker1: I have a Sheltie, a Shetland Sheepdog. His name is Buddy. How about you? What kind of dog do you have?
speaker2: A Labrador Retriever which explains jumping in a muddy lake. I bet it takes forever to dry Buddy out after a swim.

speaker1: It sure does. Luckily, he doesn't like to go swimming. He mostly stands in the shallow water and barks while I swim. Labs love the water don't they? Funny that yours doesn't like the bath, though.
response: The only thing I can imagine is that bath water is too clean for her. Shelties are really big, aren't they? What do you drive him around in?
entities: I have a Sheltie, a Shetland Sheepdog.
Funny that yours doesn't like the bath, though.

history: speaker1: What's up? I just got in from a run..
speaker2: Not too much just got back from fishing/.
speaker1: Is it spring yet where you live?
speaker2: It is, perfect weather for fishing. Do you enjoy the ocean?
speaker1: I do. My parents are from alaska, so I've seen the ocean from way up north.
speaker2: Oh alaska is nice, great fish there.
speaker1: Great fishing and hunting too. Grandpa used to hunt caribou.
speaker2: Nice, what do you do for work?
speaker1: I'm a computer programmer at a tech firm. How about you?
speaker2: I'm an assistant at a doctors office! But my true passion is fishing.
speaker1: Do you have a fishing boat?
speaker2: I do and a condo near the beach, I'm a lucky guy.
speaker1: I enjoy fishing in Alaska
speaker2: Is that your favorite spot? What is the biggest you have caught?
speaker1: Yes, it's so peaceful. I have caught a pretty big salmon. There's nothing like camping under the Northern lights, cooking a fish you just caught over a fire.
speaker2: That sounds so nice. I just cleaned my fishing boat.
speaker1: Ooh, do you have a trip planned soon or was this just a regular cleaning?
speaker2: Just my version of spring cleaning! But I would love to plan a trip soon
speaker1: That's great. Maybe we can go fishing together and trade stories. I love being out on the water. I'm a pretty good cook, too. haha
speaker2: What is your favorite meal to cook? I make a great calzone

speaker1: Calzones are delicious! I love them with spinach and mushrooms. Hmm. My favorite meal would probably be soup. I love making soup. You can put anything in it and play around. That's also how I use up a lot of my leftovers. haha
speaker2: That's good. I should use that trick. I hate throwing away leftovers but I get so sick of them so fast.

speaker1: I hear ya. I can only eat the same thing so many times in a row. Seriously, though, just throw things in a soup! My dad would call it throw-together soup. haha Start with stock or bullion and water, pick some noodles, veggies, a meat, then add sauces/cheese/seasonings until you are happy.
speaker2: That's a great idea. I always want to try a baked potato soup. Now you're making me hungry.
speaker1: Where is your favorite place to go with your boat?
speaker2: Since I live close to the ocean, I like to just sail out far and be by myself. How often do you go fishing?

speaker1: I used to go fishing every weekend. Now that my son is a little bit older though, he doesn't like fishing. Ever since he made the connection that 'chicken' is not the name of two different things, an animal and a food, and we simply eat chicken... he has unfortunately had this realization about other things, such as fish, and therefore fishing always causes tantrums unless we return the fish to the ocean and don't plan on eating it. Do you have any family that will sail with you sometimes? I agree, it's definitely nice to go out far and be alone to your thoughts every now and then!
speaker2: Sorry to hear that. If I caught a fish I'd want to eat it. Anyway, I really should plan a trip to Alaska soon. Maybe even go there in my boat.
speaker1: Would you go alone? You're always welcome to visit! I can get our guest room ready, and if others would come with you let me know and I'm sure we could make some space if you'd like.
speaker2: I'd love to stay with you. Since I've always wanted to try baked potato soup, maybe I'd get a chance to try some of yours.
speaker1: That would be awesome! I could definitely cook some up. My wife and son would be so excited to have company. Other than my parents, we usually don't have anyone over.
response: I won't take up too much space since it'll just be me. I'm single, so won't have a partner to bring with me.
entities: My wife and son would be so excited to have company. Other than my parents, we usually don't have anyone over.

speaker2: Not too much just got back from fishing/.

speaker1: I do. My parents are from alaska, so I've seen the ocean from way up north.
speaker2: Oh alaska is nice, great fish there.
speaker1: Great fishing and hunting too. Grandpa used to hunt caribou.
speaker2: Nice, what do you do for work?

speaker2: I'm an assistant at a doctors office! But my true passion is fishing.

speaker2: I do and a condo near the beach, I'm a lucky guy.
speaker1: I enjoy fishing in Alaska
speaker2: Is that your favorite spot? What is the biggest you have caught?
speaker1: Yes, it's so peaceful. I have caught a pretty big salmon. There's nothing like camping under the Northern lights, cooking a fish you just caught over a fire.
speaker2: That sounds so nice. I just cleaned my fishing boat.
speaker1: Ooh, do you have a trip planned soon or was this just a regular cleaning?
speaker2: Just my version of spring cleaning! But I would love to plan a trip soon
speaker1: That's great. Maybe we can go fishing together and trade stories. I love being out on the water. I'm a pretty good cook, too. haha
speaker2: What is your favorite meal to cook? I make a great calzone

speaker1: Calzones are delicious! I love them with spinach and mushrooms. Hmm. My favorite meal would probably be soup. I love making soup. You can put anything in it and play around. That's also how I use up a lot of my leftovers. haha
speaker2: That's good. I should use that trick. I hate throwing away leftovers but I get so sick of them so fast.

speaker1: I hear ya. I can only eat the same thing so many times in a row. Seriously, though, just throw things in a soup! My dad would call it throw-together soup. haha Start with stock or bullion and water, pick some noodles, veggies, a meat, then add sauces/cheese/seasonings until you are happy.
speaker2: That's a great idea. I always want to try a baked potato soup. Now you're making me hungry.

history: speaker1: Hello! What do you do for a living?
speaker2: I live on a large farm with beans and corn.
speaker1: Cool. How many siblings do you have?
speaker2: None, maybe because my father is a preacher.
speaker1: I'm an only child too. I do have two dogs though.
speaker2: I do like dogs, do you like country music? It's my favorite.
speaker1: I like country music. By the way..do you grow beans and corn?
speaker2: Yes and I like to drive trucks and tractors around on the farm. Tractors being my favorite.
speaker1: That would be fun. My dad was in the navy.
speaker2: That's cool. Winter is my favorite time of the year, what about you?
speaker1: We didn't have much winter since growing up I was in school in france and spain.
speaker2: Cool, but with the farm and my father being a preacher not much traveling for me.
speaker1: I had an argument with my Dad yesterday. He still thinks I should join the Navy.
speaker2: I think you should do whatever you please!
speaker1: Thank you for that encouragement. Thats so nice. How are you?
speaker2: Good thanks. Just got home from work actually! Truck driving can be exhausting on your behind.
speaker1: Are you driving the truck for the farm or another job? I hate being in a car for a long time. Makes my behind go numb.
speaker2: Yep, I transport food to and fro! It's good honest work but I won't lie, I think it ages my body a bit. Do you ever listen to country music in the car?
speaker1: Oh nice. I'm sure it is hard on your body. Thats the only music I listen to when I am driving. Do you have a favorite country song?
speaker2: Yeah! My favorite country song is anything by Billy Ray Cyrus! How about you?
speaker1: I like his new song, I Want My Mullet Back. I'm a Garth Brooks lover. I Got Friends in Low Places is my favorite probably.
speaker2: ME TOO! I love Garth Brooks as well. Any good music artists in France and Spain?
speaker1: I used to know them all but now I  only listen to American music.
speaker2: Cool. Did you live there because of your dad?
speaker1: Have you ever been to a Billy Ray Cyrus live show?
speaker2: sadly no... I never had enough money to afford tickets.
speaker1: I bet he puts on a fantastic show; I'm not sure if he tours anymore, but I think he's doing a few live events in Florida this summer.
speaker2: maybe we can go! I have enough money saved up so we can make it a whole vacation.
speaker1: I wish I could, but I just started a new job and I don't think I can ask for time off yet.
speaker2: darn.  what's the new job?

speaker1: Nothing too exciting, just working the front desk at a hotel. Still, it will give me a little breathing room and time to think about what I want to do in the future. I know I definitely do not want to join the military like my dad, and I am also not big on the idea of going back to school. I just need to find my passion. Do you feel like truck driving and helping out on the farm are what you want to do forever?
speaker2: yes.  driving tractors is definitely my favorite thing to do.  Plus I love just being out on the open road and exploring the country.
speaker1: I wish I could find something that I really love doing, but I just seem to be very apathetic towards most things. I do like music, maybe I could do something with that?
speaker2: that's a good idea.  Can you play any instruments?
speaker1: No, I definitely can't make music at all. I do, however, love listening to music and sharing my thoughts on it with others.
speaker2: maybe you could become a music reviewer?
speaker1: I thought of a cool career to look into!
speaker2: Oh really? What would that be? I always have my eyes open for career change opportunities.
speaker1: I saw a job that involved creating and testing new jelly bean flavors!  That would be kinda fun!
speaker2: Whoa! You must be brave! I wonder how that works... do they just make random flavors and the test subjects tell them what it most tastes like, and that becomes the name of the taste?

speaker1: Well, in the video I saw, they have like a giant storeroom full of every flavoring known to man, and a masterbook of recipes that combine to make different basic flavors.  Basically they just think up stuff, and then tweak the standard recipe until they are satisfied and then test it.

speaker2: I wonder if they can make tastes based on smells of things that one doesn't usually taste. And I wonder if they make tastes that imitate sounds. You know, abstract mixing of the senses in an artistic way. Would you pitch it to them when you start working there for me?
speaker1: Sure! But I probably had better come up with a few winners first before I go to far into the breach! haha.  It's an intriguing idea though. Like, what would the sound of a flute taste like?

speaker2: Exactly! And you could box it in a way that when they open the box, a flute song plays. And they basically eat jelly beans to soothing flute music. It could be really cool for children with sensory development issues.
speaker1: Wow! Maybe you and I should just go into the jelly bean business for ourselves! lol You live on a farm, so we'd have access to plenty of corn syrup! haha
response: We should. Or we could just give the idea away to the universe and hope the little seed takes root in the mind of a more industrious person!
entities: And you could box it in a way that when they open the box, a flute song plays. And they basically eat jelly beans to soothing flute music. It could be really cool for children with sensory development issues.

history: speaker1: Hi how are u today?
speaker2: I am good. Getting ready to pick my son up from school. How about you?
speaker1: Not bad just finished class awhile ago.
speaker2: Are you in college? I am thinking of going back to school.
speaker1: Yes currently. If my dad wasnt a famous musician I wouldnt be able to afford it.
speaker2: Oh what band is your dad in?
speaker1: He does the piano for the san fransisco phil symphony.
speaker2: That's awesome. I used to go to the symphony when I was a kid in britain.
speaker1: Do u like music? I love paramore.
speaker2: I do like music. Mainly classic and alternative rock.
speaker1: Do u have siblings? I have a sister who teaches.
speaker2: Yes my sister is back in england. I moved to the us 10 years ago.
speaker1: Do you have any pets? I have a bunch.
speaker2: I have one dog. What type of pets do you have?
speaker1: How did you enjoy living in England compared to the states?
speaker2: Oh it's a big cultural shock, but I like it a lot. How do you like San Francisco?
speaker1: When I go visit my dad, I do like to go to the big bridge. I do prefer to stay near my dorm though. It is so hard to be away from my fur babies.
speaker2: What kind of course are you taking?
speaker1: Equine science. I am thinking about going to vet school or else maybe studying more about cattle ranching
speaker2: So cool! I hope you fulfill those wishes. So are you an animal person?

speaker1: Oh yeah. I am way into all animals. I have studied some marine biology when I was on summer in high school, and got to do some scuba diving. But When I got out of HS, I decided I wanted to work with horses. Especially since my dog was bred to be a cattle animal.
speaker2: That sounds like the perfect work for you then! How many pets do you have?
speaker1: I have a dog, twin calico cats, a aquarium that is full of different creatures from the deep, a family of rats, a chipmunk, two parakeets and an ant farm. What about you? You ever had pets?
speaker2: Holy cow! You've got a whole zoo. I've got one dog, his name is Hank. I love him to death.

speaker1: Oh yeah, I meant besides him lol. I would love to hear about any other pets you have ever had. I don't quite have a zoo. I did let the owl go, and I rehomed my lizards. I do plan on getting a snake before too long.
speaker2: A snake?? That's cool. I also have five cats, but they're just strays that I feed outside.
speaker1: I am also thinking about getting some hamsters but that might get tricky when the snake comes along.
speaker2: Keep your hamsters in their cage and keep the snake well fed!  I think you will avoid any problems, but do you have a place for the snake?
speaker1: Yeah, we made room in the living room for a big tank for it. We will keep the hamsters somewhere else if we get them. I just have to figure out what kind of snake I want to get.
speaker2: I can't believe all the animals you have in your home!  Do you have any issues between your animals or do they all get along?
speaker1: They get along and we have a pretty big house and a farm. The dogs and cats usually live out in the barn, but they do like to come inside sometimes.
speaker2: That sounds so amazing!  I've been thinking about getting some fish and pygmy frogs. I find aquariums so relaxing.
speaker1: That sounds awesome. If you need some advice on them let me know. We have some frogs that live around our ponds, but never had one myself.
speaker2: Oh, I will be calling you for sure!  There weren't a lot of animals around me back in England, so I am making up for lost time!
speaker1: I can image. Animals are awesome and they help you out of depression. And just make you feel better all around.
speaker2: I know I wouldn't know what to do without Hank.  He never judges me and just wants me to feel happy.  Even those stray cats seem to know when I'm having a tough day.
speaker1: They are very good at that. I am so glad you have Hank he sounds like a really great dog.

speaker2: I was really lucky.  He has a mild temperament and has never really given me problems.  He can be a little protective of me, but once he knows I am in no danger, he is wonderful with strangers.
speaker1: I've decided that I am going to get some hamsters, too! We will just keep them in a separate room from the snake to avoid any problems.
response: Wow, I thought my dog and five cats was a lot of animals but you sure have me beat. How do you like living with so many animals?
entities: Animals are awesome and they help you out of depression. And just make you feel better all around.
I've decided that I am going to get some hamsters, too! We will just keep them in a separate room from the snake to avoid any problems.

history: speaker1: Hello, how is it goin?
speaker2: Great! How about you?
speaker1: Great. Are you male or female?
speaker2: Female, love to have fun going places and trying new things. What about you?
speaker1: I am more of a family man, I love spending time with my sons.
speaker2: I have two sons myself. They are the true loves of my life.
speaker1: I agree, the best thing that has happened to me in my life.
speaker2: Do you like music? My tastes vary greatly...maroon 5, the rolling stones, brad paisley, luke bryant.
speaker1: I am lifelong fan of tupac shakur.
speaker2: Wow! What about your social life? Dinner and a movie or concerts and dancing?
speaker1: Yes, I love all kinds of cuisines mexican, italian, chinese.
speaker2: Love chinese and italian!! Mexican kills my stomach.
speaker1: I found a great new Chinese restaurant last night!
speaker2: Oh that's great! What's it called?
speaker1: China Dragon. I know... Corny name, but it was great. They have the best szechuan beef in the world.
speaker2: Really? It's hard to believe that, but I guess I'll take your word on it. Did you bring your boys there?
speaker1: Yeah. They love Chinese food too. They both had been out of town for a while, so it was good to see them.
speaker2: Ah, that's great. Only one of my sons loves Chinese food as much as I do. The other really just likes Italian food, so it can be difficult to decide where to go.
speaker1: It sounds like an international fight!!  My sons just got back from studying abroad. They are leaving again in a few months.
speaker2: It's nice that you got to spend some time with them. I'd be so worried if my boys traveled so far away. Luckily it will be a long time before they're old enough.

history: speaker1: Good afternoon how are you doing.
speaker2: I am doing well, thank you.
speaker1: I am babysitting my five grandchildren.
speaker2: Holy cow, you have five grandchildren? How do you do it?
speaker1: Yes I love taking them to the beach even though fall is my favorite season.
speaker2: Why is fall your favorite season. I love to barbecue hot dogs at the beach.
speaker1: I am listening to my favorite bands styx and journey all day.
speaker2: I am listening to my favorite band black sabbath. Are you into classic rock?
speaker1: No, but I just tried mediterranean food and loved it.
speaker2: Do you prefer beef or chicken shwarma?
speaker1: I prefer chicken shwarma over beef.
speaker2: Me too. I love mine with babaganoush. Dude I am not looking forward to work.
speaker1: What is your favorite Black Sabbath song?
speaker2: They have a lot of good songs, but my favorite would have to be Iron Man. Have you heard that one?
speaker1: Yes, for sure.  Was Ozzy Osbourne the lead singer at that time?
speaker2: I am not 100 percent sure. I just know that I love listening to them at the beach!
speaker1: My grandkids love the beach, we like to collect shells and build sand castles.  I hope you don't play the music too loud when you are there.
speaker2: No don't worry, only loud enough for me to hear. Although I do love the beach, I haven't gotten a chance to head down there a lot this year.
speaker1: Well if you are interested, I rented a place on the beach for a month.  You bring the hotdogs and we'll have a bbq and enjoy the sand.
speaker2: That would be amazing, thank you! Can I also bring my family, assuming we can all get out of work? I think my nieces and nephews will get along great with your grandkids.
speaker1: Sure that will be great.  I love having kids around and they seem to entertain each other which leaves more time for adults to be adults.
speaker2: That's right. And maybe you can play some Journey songs for me, and I'll play you some more Black Sabbath.
speaker1: Either way, as long as we don't have to listen to what the kids listen to these days, we should be good.  I'll send you the address later.
speaker2: Thank you very much, I can't wait.
speaker1: I made a really good humus recipe I will have to try with my next batch of chicken shwarma.
speaker2: If it's good, send it to me so I can try it with my chicken and babaganoush.  Are there any other Mediterranean foods you like?
speaker1: Do you ever make any vegaterian humus? I love all Mediterranean foods thats probably why I'm still hanging onto my 15lbs I gained last year. haha
speaker2: I usually eat humus along with some sort of meat. Wow - 15 pounds! Maybe it was your month at the beach that made you put on the weight. What do your grankids like to eat?
speaker1: My grandkids are monsters haha. No, they aren't picky at all the benefit is that they are so active that they can eat whatever they want. How was your last concert on the beach?
speaker2: It's good that they are not picky. My nieces and nephews hardly eat anything. I definitely don't go to the beach for a concert, but just to relax and listen to some Black Sabbath.
speaker1: Ah. Good ole Ozzzy huh?
speaker2: Yes, back in his glory days he could really sing. Now, maybe, not so much. His voice was never as good as the lead singer of Journey, do you think?
speaker1: Its funny you mention Journey, they are my favorite band. I've seen them in person over a dozen times even with the new lead singer and they are just as good.
speaker2: That is fantastic. It's hard to beat live music! I only got to see Black Sabbath once, but it was great experience.
speaker1: What year did you go see them?
speaker2: I think. it might have been 1990. Those years get a little fuzzy. I think I spent two weeks at the beach that year, as I recall.
speaker1: How old are your nieces and nephews?
speaker2: They're 12, 13, 14, and 2. I enjoy having another little one because I missed when the other 3 were little and actually wanted to spend time with me and not their phones.lol
speaker1: Yeah that's the trouble these days isn't it they are only interested in phones and computers.
response: Yeah, a lot of adults aren't much better to be honest but that's just how life grows and evolves I guess. It definitely has it's advantages and disadvantages. Are they going to spend time with you down at the beach this summer?
entities: I think I spent two weeks at the beach that year, as I recall.
Yeah that's the trouble these days isn't it they are only interested in phones and computers.

history: speaker1: I really like to scuba dive, how about you?
speaker2: Not really, I prefer going to the gym.
speaker1: Im an x marine I love going to the gym never gave up that hobby.
speaker2: Do you have any other hobbies?
speaker1: Yes I breed snakes,and and other reptiles pays pretty well to be honest.
speaker2: Thats very cool! I like driving my wrangler.
speaker1: I love driving my jeep when im in hawaii especially around honolulu.
speaker2: I hear they have great vegan food in hawaii.
speaker1: Yeah they do very much so,i moved there after my divorce from my wife.
speaker2: Hope youre having fun out there.
speaker1: I love it here so much after 3 times of going I decided to stay.
speaker2: Ill have to go check it out with my husband.
speaker1: Sounds like a plan you too wont regret it!
speaker2: He is a lawyer we always talk about going.
speaker1: I would love to get together if you and your husband decide to visit Hawaii.
speaker2: That would be fantastic! Are you based in Honolulu?
speaker1: Yes I am. Honolulu is the place to be. Hopefully you can her down here soon.
speaker2: I'd love that! Do you have any suggestions as to where we should stay while we're there?
speaker1: There is a very nice hotel that i could get you a discount at i will email you all the details.
speaker2: You're awesome! My husband has been so stressed with work lately that I think he's due for a vacation.
speaker1: Oh yeah work can for sure get to you sometimes. Honestly you both deserve a well rested break to relax.
speaker2: It's very true. How crowded do the beaches tend to get? Are there any secrets to getting a good spot?

speaker1: Yeah it for sure gets busy here during peak times, but as a local i know all the best spots that only the people that live here know about. I will give you a grand tour of all the best places.
speaker2: I can't wait! In my experience, trips are always better when you know a local.
speaker1: Yeah they are the locals seem to know all the trade secrets to a great vacation without being in the middle of the chaos.
speaker2: How long ago was your divorce, if I may ask? I know you moved there afterwards.
speaker1: I just tried out a new restaurant for lunch that will be really popular soon. You had better get down here and try it before it is impossible to get into.
speaker2: Tell me all about it!  I am working on my husband to get him to approve the Honolulu vacation.  When is the best time to go to avoid all those tourists (I know I would be one too)?
speaker1: The offseason in Honolulu would be the winter months.  You can avoid the crowds then, and your entire vacation would be cheaper with offseason prices.
speaker2: I think that's when I will try to go.  Maybe the restaurant won't be too crowded?  What is on the menu?

speaker1: Traditional Hawaiian food that are local favorites.  There's plenty of other restaurants here to choose from, so I'm sure you'll love the food.  Will this be your first time visiting Honolulu?

speaker2: Yes.  We were supposed to go two years ago, but something came up and we had to vacation a little closer to home.  We are definitely ready. Are there some places that you would recommend that maybe most tourists don't know about?

speaker1: Depends on the types of attractions you're into.  There's plenty of hole in the wall restaurants that only locals know about so be sure to ask the hotel staff.  What are looking forward to most once you're here?
speaker2: Thanks so much for the suggestions!  I think I really want to go to the beach and I really want to visit Diamond Head.  I hear it's breathtaking.
speaker1: The beaches here are amazing ofcourse.  This will be an incredible romantic getaway.  How long have you been married?
response: 10 years next month!  I am thinking of telling my husband to hold off on exchanging anniversary gifts and just put it into my little 'Aloha Fund!'
entities: How long have you been married?

history: speaker1: Hi. I work in a fast food restaurant that serves the best ice cream.
speaker2: What a fun job! I am not a big fan of cold after living in alaska for three years.
speaker1: I can understand that. I'll be going to college next year so, I need the money.
speaker2: Congrats! What will you be studying? I am hoping to retire on a beach soon.
speaker1: Neuroscience. I volunteer at a research lab now.
speaker2: That sounds fascinating. I don't know much about neuroscience but I know I love my smart car!
speaker1: Awesome! Believe it or not, I'm also a scout....an eagle scout!
speaker2: On your honor? My parents are from the north and never introduced me to scouting.
speaker1: I've done it for years....don't plan to give it up anytime soon.
speaker2: My hair is blonde and I have blue eyes. What do you look like?
speaker1: Dark with hazel eyes and a lots of personality.
speaker2: I can tell, what do you do for fun?
speaker1: I live by the beach so, I like to fish and swim.
speaker2: I might have to move in with you when I retire!
speaker1: How long have you had your smart car?
speaker2: I've had it for a good five years or so now. It's definitely been helping me to save up for retirement, and it's actually kind of fun once you get used to it.
speaker1: I bet, I have been wanting to get one. How long does it usually take to fully charge?
speaker2: Oh, about a couple hours or so. It's just important to remember to recharge it before you need to go out!
speaker1: That has always been my thing, I don't want to wait forever at places for the car to charge
speaker2: Yeah, I probably wouldn't have gotten it if I had to regularly drive long distances. I mostly just use it to get around town, so I can just recharge at home most of the time.
speaker1: I definitely need to consider getting one than! What beach are you hoping to retire on one day?
speaker2: I haven't made up my mind just yet. It'd be nice to find a place in Hawaii, although I'll need to save up a lot more for that.
speaker1: Hawaii is amazing, I live by a beach and it is amazing to be within walking distance of the water
speaker2: I'm sure it is! What beach do you live near?
speaker1: I live near Daytona Beach, gets a little touristy in the summer, so the beaches are packed, but it is fun.
speaker2: Hmm, I probably would've enjoyed that in my younger days. But I think I'd prefer somewhere a bit quieter for my twilight years.
speaker1: I just went to the beach after work and it was really busy, it must be tourist season.
speaker2: Did you go swimming at the beach?
speaker1: Yes, I love the ocean. I prefer it when it's quieter though. There wasn't much room to go for a walk or be alone with my thoughts.
speaker2: Was the water more calm than it has been recently?
speaker1: Yes, it was calm but lots were splashing around. I swam out pretty far though.
speaker2: I got caught up in a rip tide once and it pulled me out so far.  I'm always nervous about the ocean now.

speaker1: I know. I experienced that also when I was small. I was pulled under. Luckily it wasn't too far from shore. Very scary though. Somehow I overcame my fear. But, it's always in the back of my mind.
speaker2: How did you manage to overcome it?

speaker1: Somehow my love of the ocean was enough. I also did a lot of meditation with ocean sounds. I think that helped me to see the ocean as a calming place not a place to fear. Ultimately, I just had to get back in the water. I took it slow though and stayed close to shore for quite a while, venturing out when it seemed safe. Today, I just wanted to get past the crowds so I swam out.
response: I think I should try that sometime.  I'd love to get back out there again.

history: speaker1: Hi. I just got home from school. What's up with you?
speaker2: Hey there just got done looking at furniture online. How are you today?
speaker1: I'm good. What kind of furniture are you getting?
speaker2: Loveseat. I hope it will not collect pet fur.
speaker1: Do you have dogs, cats, or a mixture of both?
speaker2: 2 doggies. I love my fur babies.
speaker1: Aww! We have a dog and a cat, but the cat only really likes mom.
speaker2: Cats can be that way. My dogs will be happy when the house is finished.
speaker1: Are you doing major renovations like on hgtv?
speaker2: Yeah and the dogs dont care for all the workers..
speaker1: My dad's a steel worker. It's really noisy there!
speaker2: I bet. Well I need to get to the mall soon for work..
speaker1: Ok, I need to do my homework. It was nice chatting with you!
speaker2: After work I will grill steaks. Drop by later if you can..
speaker1: How are your home renovations coming along?
speaker2: It's coming along, slowly but surely. Dealing with contractors is always a pain. It's as though they're incapable of meeting their own deadlines!
speaker1: Yes, I can imagine. Are you able to do any of the work yoursef?
speaker2: Only certain basics like painting and such. With my work schedule, it's hard to get much done.
speaker1: I'd offer to help you, but I'm afraid I'm not very handy.  I tend to take after my mother more than my dad.
speaker2: Haha I appreciate the thought. How have things been at school lately?
speaker1: Pretty good. But it takes a lot of time too.  My parents warned me about going into nuclear physics;.
speaker2: Wow, you're very ambitious! I can't even begin to imagine what the workload must be.
speaker1: Yeah, I try to explain it to my parents but they don't understand.  My dad says the only thing you need to know about physics is to not drop an I-beam on your foot.
speaker2: Haha in your dad's defense, he's in a very different line of work. They're not too concerned about theory over at the steel mills!
speaker1: I suppose not.  He does go nuclear sometimes though! lol  has the mall been busy lately?
speaker2: It's been pretty hectic, yes! I'm amazed at how many people try to steal the most random junk from stores. I work in the central security office, so I see stuff on camera all day long.
speaker1: I have been studying hard the last few days and my dog and cat have been very needy. It's hard to get some things done with them around.
speaker2: Yeah I bet it is! I don't know how you do it as well as you do. Are your parents starting to understand how busy you are yet?
speaker1: Nope, since my parents never attended college they dont tend to understand the amount of time it consumes.
speaker2: I'm sorry. But hopefully they'll realize how hard you're working at some point. What's been up with the pets? Do you think they're sensing your stress level and reacting to that?
speaker1: I think they are noticing that i am not spending as much time with them anymore and they are just trying to get attention. Have you had this problem with your 2 dogs?

speaker2: Definitely. Whenever I take someone else's shift at the mall, they get needy. They jump on me when I get home and then refuse to eat unless I sit there with them. It's definitely kind of frustrating. I mean, it's nice to be liked, but sometimes you just want to be solo.
speaker1: I understand that, i could defentily go for some alone time right now. My mom is always on me and my pets never leave me alone. What do you plan on renovating?
response: My next project is the kitchen. It's got an '80s vibe to it and it's just not my style.

What do you plan on renovating?

history: speaker1: What's up? I just got in from a run..
speaker2: Not too much just got back from fishing/.
speaker1: Is it spring yet where you live?
speaker2: It is, perfect weather for fishing. Do you enjoy the ocean?
speaker1: I do. My parents are from alaska, so I've seen the ocean from way up north.
speaker2: Oh alaska is nice, great fish there.
speaker1: Great fishing and hunting too. Grandpa used to hunt caribou.
speaker2: Nice, what do you do for work?
speaker1: I'm a computer programmer at a tech firm. How about you?
speaker2: I'm an assistant at a doctors office! But my true passion is fishing.
speaker1: Do you have a fishing boat?
speaker2: I do and a condo near the beach, I'm a lucky guy.
speaker1: I enjoy fishing in Alaska
speaker2: Is that your favorite spot? What is the biggest you have caught?
speaker1: Yes, it's so peaceful. I have caught a pretty big salmon. There's nothing like camping under the Northern lights, cooking a fish you just caught over a fire.
speaker2: That sounds so nice. I just cleaned my fishing boat.
speaker1: Ooh, do you have a trip planned soon or was this just a regular cleaning?
speaker2: Just my version of spring cleaning! But I would love to plan a trip soon
speaker1: That's great. Maybe we can go fishing together and trade stories. I love being out on the water. I'm a pretty good cook, too. haha
speaker2: What is your favorite meal to cook? I make a great calzone

speaker1: Calzones are delicious! I love them with spinach and mushrooms. Hmm. My favorite meal would probably be soup. I love making soup. You can put anything in it and play around. That's also how I use up a lot of my leftovers. haha
speaker2: That's good. I should use that trick. I hate throwing away leftovers but I get so sick of them so fast.

speaker1: I hear ya. I can only eat the same thing so many times in a row. Seriously, though, just throw things in a soup! My dad would call it throw-together soup. haha Start with stock or bullion and water, pick some noodles, veggies, a meat, then add sauces/cheese/seasonings until you are happy.
speaker2: That's a great idea. I always want to try a baked potato soup. Now you're making me hungry.
speaker1: Where is your favorite place to go with your boat?
response: Since I live close to the ocean, I like to just sail out far and be by myself. How often do you go fishing?
entities: I enjoy fishing in Alaska
Where is your favorite place to go with your boat?

history: speaker1: Hi how are u today?
speaker2: I am good. Getting ready to pick my son up from school. How about you?
speaker1: Not bad just finished class awhile ago.
speaker2: Are you in college? I am thinking of going back to school.
speaker1: Yes currently. If my dad wasnt a famous musician I wouldnt be able to afford it.
speaker2: Oh what band is your dad in?
speaker1: He does the piano for the san fransisco phil symphony.
speaker2: That's awesome. I used to go to the symphony when I was a kid in britain.
speaker1: Do u like music? I love paramore.
speaker2: I do like music. Mainly classic and alternative rock.
speaker1: Do u have siblings? I have a sister who teaches.
speaker2: Yes my sister is back in england. I moved to the us 10 years ago.
speaker1: Do you have any pets? I have a bunch.
speaker2: I have one dog. What type of pets do you have?
speaker1: How did you enjoy living in England compared to the states?
speaker2: Oh it's a big cultural shock, but I like it a lot. How do you like San Francisco?
speaker1: When I go visit my dad, I do like to go to the big bridge. I do prefer to stay near my dorm though. It is so hard to be away from my fur babies.
speaker2: What kind of course are you taking?
speaker1: Equine science. I am thinking about going to vet school or else maybe studying more about cattle ranching
speaker2: So cool! I hope you fulfill those wishes. So are you an animal person?

speaker1: Oh yeah. I am way into all animals. I have studied some marine biology when I was on summer in high school, and got to do some scuba diving. But When I got out of HS, I decided I wanted to work with horses. Especially since my dog was bred to be a cattle animal.
speaker2: That sounds like the perfect work for you then! How many pets do you have?
speaker1: I have a dog, twin calico cats, a aquarium that is full of different creatures from the deep, a family of rats, a chipmunk, two parakeets and an ant farm. What about you? You ever had pets?
speaker2: Holy cow! You've got a whole zoo. I've got one dog, his name is Hank. I love him to death.

speaker1: Oh yeah, I meant besides him lol. I would love to hear about any other pets you have ever had. I don't quite have a zoo. I did let the owl go, and I rehomed my lizards. I do plan on getting a snake before too long.
speaker2: A snake?? That's cool. I also have five cats, but they're just strays that I feed outside.
speaker1: I am also thinking about getting some hamsters but that might get tricky when the snake comes along.
speaker2: Keep your hamsters in their cage and keep the snake well fed!  I think you will avoid any problems, but do you have a place for the snake?
speaker1: Yeah, we made room in the living room for a big tank for it. We will keep the hamsters somewhere else if we get them. I just have to figure out what kind of snake I want to get.
speaker2: I can't believe all the animals you have in your home!  Do you have any issues between your animals or do they all get along?
speaker1: They get along and we have a pretty big house and a farm. The dogs and cats usually live out in the barn, but they do like to come inside sometimes.
response: That sounds so amazing!  I've been thinking about getting some fish and pygmy frogs. I find aquariums so relaxing.

history: speaker1: Hello, how is it goin?
speaker2: Great! How about you?
speaker1: Great. Are you male or female?
speaker2: Female, love to have fun going places and trying new things. What about you?
speaker1: I am more of a family man, I love spending time with my sons.
speaker2: I have two sons myself. They are the true loves of my life.
speaker1: I agree, the best thing that has happened to me in my life.
speaker2: Do you like music? My tastes vary greatly...maroon 5, the rolling stones, brad paisley, luke bryant.
speaker1: I am lifelong fan of tupac shakur.
speaker2: Wow! What about your social life? Dinner and a movie or concerts and dancing?
speaker1: Yes, I love all kinds of cuisines mexican, italian, chinese.
speaker2: Love chinese and italian!! Mexican kills my stomach.
speaker1: I found a great new Chinese restaurant last night!
speaker2: Oh that's great! What's it called?
speaker1: China Dragon. I know... Corny name, but it was great. They have the best szechuan beef in the world.
speaker2: Really? It's hard to believe that, but I guess I'll take your word on it. Did you bring your boys there?
speaker1: Yeah. They love Chinese food too. They both had been out of town for a while, so it was good to see them.
speaker2: Ah, that's great. Only one of my sons loves Chinese food as much as I do. The other really just likes Italian food, so it can be difficult to decide where to go.
speaker1: It sounds like an international fight!!  My sons just got back from studying abroad. They are leaving again in a few months.
speaker2: It's nice that you got to spend some time with them. I'd be so worried if my boys traveled so far away. Luckily it will be a long time before they're old enough.
speaker1: It's stressful and I worry all the time, but I am happy for them. Enjoying them while you can. They grow up fast.
speaker2: Oh yeah, definitely. Where have your boys been studying?
speaker1: They have been in Spain and they are going to Italy next. The European tour!!
speaker2: My younger son would be so jealous. They must be eating really well over there!
speaker1: One of my sons just told me that he has a Spanish girlfriend now.
speaker2: Congratulations to your son! Is he happy? Do they seem to be a good match? Have you met her, or gotten a chance to talk to her yet? That's exciting!
speaker1: They seem very much in love. I'm so happy for him. My other sons seem to be jealous since they're single still. She's very polite and mature for her age.
speaker2: Did they meet at school? What is your son studying? And is she studying the same thing? That's great to hear. Young love is beautiful.
speaker1: They met in school. They're both in college and studying to be chefs. I joked that now I get to eat food prepared by two trained chefs instead of one!

speaker2: Oh my goodness! I definitely see some tasty dinners in your future! No wonder they get along so well. Food is the way to one's heart, and it sounds like they will both be amazing chefs! Maybe they can even open their own restaurant someday if things go well! Let me know and I'll come to the grand opening, whether it be in Europe or anywhere else in the world!
speaker1: Funny enough, my son is great at making Italian food, and his girlfriend knows a few Chinese recipes. So you'd probably love both of the dishes they could prepare.

speaker2: My mouth is watering just thinking about it. I'll bring my sons along too! A Chinese and Italian fusion would be perfect for my family to enjoy! There would be no arguments over what to eat.
speaker1: You'd definitely be on the guest list! Speaking of which, how are your sons doing? Anything new with them?

speaker2: One of their birthdays is coming up. They will be thirteen. We are planning on throwing a surprise party, but sometimes it's hard to pull him away from his video games so it shouldn't be too hard to sneak his friends into the house. I can only hope we can pull him away from his computer long enough to get him to walk down the stairs. Teenagers. Can't live with them... and can't live with them.
speaker1: I know what you mean. My youngest son is addicted to social media and video games as well. He comes out of his room to eat, then I don't see him until the morning.

speaker2: At least they can pull themselves away from virtual reality long enough to keep themselves alive in real life. Ha. I'm trying to encourage him to get into programming or writing. My son was always very creative, I feel like he could be a great writer or game developer someday, but all he wants to do is co-op with his friends.

speaker2: That's so sweet of them! What dishes did they make?

history: speaker1: Good afternoon how are you doing.
speaker2: I am doing well, thank you.
speaker1: I am babysitting my five grandchildren.
speaker2: Holy cow, you have five grandchildren? How do you do it?
speaker1: Yes I love taking them to the beach even though fall is my favorite season.
speaker2: Why is fall your favorite season. I love to barbecue hot dogs at the beach.
speaker1: I am listening to my favorite bands styx and journey all day.
speaker2: I am listening to my favorite band black sabbath. Are you into classic rock?
speaker1: No, but I just tried mediterranean food and loved it.
speaker2: Do you prefer beef or chicken shwarma?
speaker1: I prefer chicken shwarma over beef.
speaker2: Me too. I love mine with babaganoush. Dude I am not looking forward to work.
speaker1: What is your favorite Black Sabbath song?
speaker2: They have a lot of good songs, but my favorite would have to be Iron Man. Have you heard that one?
speaker1: Yes, for sure.  Was Ozzy Osbourne the lead singer at that time?
speaker2: I am not 100 percent sure. I just know that I love listening to them at the beach!
speaker1: My grandkids love the beach, we like to collect shells and build sand castles.  I hope you don't play the music too loud when you are there.
speaker2: No don't worry, only loud enough for me to hear. Although I do love the beach, I haven't gotten a chance to head down there a lot this year.
speaker1: Well if you are interested, I rented a place on the beach for a month.  You bring the hotdogs and we'll have a bbq and enjoy the sand.
speaker2: That would be amazing, thank you! Can I also bring my family, assuming we can all get out of work? I think my nieces and nephews will get along great with your grandkids.
speaker1: Sure that will be great.  I love having kids around and they seem to entertain each other which leaves more time for adults to be adults.
speaker2: That's right. And maybe you can play some Journey songs for me, and I'll play you some more Black Sabbath.
speaker1: Either way, as long as we don't have to listen to what the kids listen to these days, we should be good.  I'll send you the address later.
speaker2: Thank you very much, I can't wait.
speaker1: I made a really good humus recipe I will have to try with my next batch of chicken shwarma.
speaker2: If it's good, send it to me so I can try it with my chicken and babaganoush.  Are there any other Mediterranean foods you like?
speaker1: Do you ever make any vegaterian humus? I love all Mediterranean foods thats probably why I'm still hanging onto my 15lbs I gained last year. haha
speaker2: I usually eat humus along with some sort of meat. Wow - 15 pounds! Maybe it was your month at the beach that made you put on the weight. What do your grankids like to eat?
speaker1: My grandkids are monsters haha. No, they aren't picky at all the benefit is that they are so active that they can eat whatever they want. How was your last concert on the beach?
response: It's good that they are not picky. My nieces and nephews hardly eat anything. I definitely don't go to the beach for a concert, but just to relax and listen to some Black Sabbath.
entities: I think my nieces and nephews will get along great with your grandkids.

history: speaker1: Hey, buddy...how's it going?
speaker2: Doing great weather is great for playing baseball. You?
speaker1: Waiting for some better weather to get out diving! Ever been scuba diving?
speaker2: No but I do enjoy having seafood.
speaker1: Best seafood I've ever had was as a marine stationed in hawaii.
speaker2: I would love to goto hawaii, but currently stuck working on my marketing degree.
speaker1: Retired now, so will go for the 4th time soon!.
speaker2: I would like to do a design ad later for hawaii, when I go visit.
speaker1: Yep, just got divorced so it's just me and my two pets snakes now..
speaker2: Good time to learn new things. I love learning new languages.
speaker1: What languages can you speak now?
speaker2: Chinese and english. Learning japanese since I like playing baseball.
speaker1: One of my pet snakes escaped today! Guess where I found him?
speaker2: I hope it wasn't curled up on the couch!
speaker1: Nope that would not have been good. He was in my tumble dryer. I nearly didn't see him when i put the clothes in there from the wash.
speaker2: Perhaps the dryer was still warm after the last use and he enjoyed the temperature.  Sometimes I wish I could crawl into a dryer to warm up!
speaker1: Yes that must of been it. I should of checked there first really but its the furthest place he could have gone in it didn't even cross my mind. But he is safely back in his enclosure now.
speaker2: Do you think the snakes might have contributed to your divorce?
speaker1: No they didn't i got them after the divorce as i always wanted to have snakes and she didn't. But now i get to do what i like which is great.

speaker2: I generally do what I want too, sometimes it doesn't work out with my studies...I have been trying to finish this marketing degree for 6 years now.  Probably time to strap in and hit the books!
speaker1: Yeah school can be tough to get through. Especially if you don't have the right mind set. But you have come so far you can do this.
speaker2: I'm just spread a little thin now...school, learning foreign languages, baseball, etc.  I really need to focus on one at a time.  Any tips for when you were in marines?

speaker1: Honestly at first i didn't take things as serious as i should off. You just need to set up yourself in your mind that you need to put in the work to get to the place you want to be in life, even when times get hard just push through and it will all be worth it in the end.
speaker2: Good advice. I will never be a professional ball player or work at the United Nations as a translator, so better to focus on marketing.
speaker1: I obtained two tickets to the local baseball team's home game.
speaker2: That's great! Do you like baseball? I have never gone.
speaker1: Yeah, I used to play all the time when I was a kid, and I taught my kids how to play too.
speaker2: I wish I could play more, but I have not had time recently since I have been busy studying for school.
speaker1: It's a shame you've never had the chance to go to a game. I'm sure you'd enjoy it given the fact that you've played it a fair bit.

speaker2: Yes, I agree. Too much time playing, and not enough time watching and enjoying the sport! I am very excited to finally get my marketing degree, though. Have you done any dives since we spoke last?

speaker2: Congrats! What will you be studying? I am hoping to retire on a beach soon.
speaker1: Neuroscience. I volunteer at a research lab now.

speaker1: Dark with hazel eyes and a lots of personality.

speaker1: I live by the beach so, I like to fish and swim.
speaker2: I might have to move in with you when I retire!

speaker2: I've had it for a good five years or so now. It's definitely been helping me to save up for retirement, and it's actually kind of fun once you get used to it.

speaker2: Oh, about a couple hours or so. It's just important to remember to recharge it before you need to go out!

speaker2: Yeah, I probably wouldn't have gotten it if I had to regularly drive long distances. I mostly just use it to get around town, so I can just recharge at home most of the time.

speaker2: I haven't made up my mind just yet. It'd be nice to find a place in Hawaii, although I'll need to save up a lot more for that.
